name: Beryllium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: beryl, a mineral (ultimately from the name of Belur in southern India)

name: Sodium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: English soda (the symbol Na is derived from New Latin natrium, coined from German Natron, 'natron')

name: Magnesium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Magnesia, a district of Eastern Thessaly in Greece

name: Aluminium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: alumina, from Latin alumen (gen. aluminis), 'bitter salt, alum'

name: Potassium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: New Latin potassa, 'potash' (the symbol K is derived from Latin kalium)

name: Titanium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Titans, the sons of the Earth goddess of Greek mythology

name: Vanadium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Vanadis, an Old Norse name for the Scandinavian goddess Freyja

name: Manganese
wikipedia_origin_of_name: corrupted from magnesia negra; see Magnesium

name: Iron
wikipedia_origin_of_name: English word (the symbol Fe is derived from Latin ferrum)

name: Nickel
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Nickel, a mischievous sprite of German miner mythology

name: Copper
wikipedia_origin_of_name: English word, from Latin cuprum, from Ancient Greek Kýpros 'Cyprus'

name: Zinc
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Most likely from German Zinke, 'prong' or 'tooth', though some suggest Persian sang, 'stone'

name: Arsenic
wikipedia_origin_of_name: French arsenic, from Greek arsenikón 'yellow arsenic' (influenced by arsenikós, 'masculine' or 'virile'), from a West Asian wanderword ultimately from Old Iranian *zarniya-ka, 'golden'

name: Niobium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Niobe, daughter of king Tantalus from Greek mythology

name: Molybdenum
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Greek molýbdaina, 'piece of lead', from mólybdos, 'lead', due to confusuion with lead ore galena (PbS)

name: Palladium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: the asteroid Pallas, considered a planet at the time

name: Silver
wikipedia_origin_of_name: English word (The symbol is derived from Latin argentum)

name: Cadmium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: New Latin cadmia, from King Kadmos

name: Indium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Latin indicum, 'indigo' (colour found in its spectrum)

name: Tin
wikipedia_origin_of_name: English word (The symbol is derived from Latin stannum)

name: Antimony
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Latin antimonium, the origin of which is uncertain: folk etymologies suggest it is derived from Greek antí ('against') + mónos ('alone'), or Old French anti-moine, 'Monk's bane', but it could plausibly be from or related to Arabic ʾiṯmid, 'antimony', reformatted as a Latin word. (The symbol is derived from Latin stibium 'stibnite'.)

name: Xenon
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Greek xénon, neuter form of xénos 'strange'

name: Cerium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: the dwarf planet Ceres, considered a planet at the time

name: Samarium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: samarskite, a mineral named after Colonel Vasili Samarsky-Bykhovets, Russian mine official

name: Gadolinium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: gadolinite, a mineral named after Johan Gadolin, Finnish chemist, physicist and mineralogist

name: Thulium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Thule, the ancient name for an unclear northern location

name: Tantalum
wikipedia_origin_of_name: King Tantalus, father of Niobe from Greek mythology

name: Tungsten
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Swedish tung sten, 'heavy stone' (The symbol is from wolfram, the old name of the tungsten mineral wolframite)

name: Iridium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Iris, the Greek goddess of the rainbow

name: Gold
wikipedia_origin_of_name: English word (the symbol Au is derived from Latin aurum)

name: Mercury
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Mercury, Roman god of commerce, communication, and luck, known for his speed and mobility (the symbol Hg derives from the element's Latin name hydrargyrum, from Greek hydrárgyros, 'water-silver')

name: Lead
wikipedia_origin_of_name: English word (the symbol Pb is derived from Latin plumbum)

name: Bismuth
wikipedia_origin_of_name: German Wismut, from weiß Masse 'white mass', unless from Arabic

name: Polonium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Latin Polonia, 'Poland' (the home country of Marie Curie)

name: Thorium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Thor, the Scandinavian god of thunder

name: Protactinium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: proto- (from Greek prôtos, 'first, before') + actinium, which is produced through the radioactive decay of protactinium

name: Uranium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Uranus, the seventh planet in the Solar System

name: Neptunium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Neptune, the eighth planet in the Solar System

name: Plutonium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: the dwarf planet Pluto, considered the ninth planet in the Solar System at the time

name: Americium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: The Americas, as the element was first synthesised on the continent, by analogy with europium

name: Curium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Pierre Curie and Marie Curie, French physicists and chemists

name: Berkelium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Berkeley, California, where the element was first synthesised, by analogy with terbium

name: Californium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: California, where the element was first synthesised

name: Mendelevium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Dmitri Mendeleev, Russian chemist and inventor who proposed the periodic table

name: Nobelium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Alfred Nobel, Swedish chemist and engineer

name: Rutherfordium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Ernest Rutherford, chemist and physicist from New Zealand

name: Dubnium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Dubna, Russia, where the Joint Institute for Nuclear Research is located

name: Hassium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: New Latin Hassia, 'Hesse' (a state in Germany)

name: Darmstadtium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Darmstadt, Germany, where the element was first synthesised

name: Nihonium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Japanese Nihon, 'Japan' (where the element was first synthesised)

name: Flerovium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Flerov Laboratory of Nuclear Reactions, part of JINR, where the element was synthesised; itself named after Georgy Flyorov, Russian physicist

name: Moscovium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Moscow Oblast, Russia, where the element was first synthesised

name: Livermorium
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory in Livermore, California, which collaborated with JINR on its synthesis

name: Tennessine
wikipedia_origin_of_name: Tennessee, United States (where Oak Ridge National Laboratory is located)
